2. Basic Distribution of Charges

A quick peek at the histogram shows that majority of the charges lies under 15000, with no significant dependence on sex.

paste("Mean: ",mean(df$charges))
## [1] "Mean:  13270.4222651413"

quantile(df$charges)

ggplot(df,aes(x=charges)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill=sex)) +
  labs(x="Insurance Charges", y="", title = "Histogram of charges by sex")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

3. Total Charges Dependency on Features

The dependency of total charges on various features in studied using a pair plot, colored by sex. For this plot, the factored features such as smoker and region are converted to numeric. A strong correlation is observed for being a smoker, followed by age and bmi. No strong dependence on region or number of children.

df2=df
df2$smoker<-as.numeric(df2$smoker)
df2$region<-as.numeric(df2$region)
ggpairs(df2,aes(colour=sex))

4. Regression - Charges dependent on smoker, age and bmi

An attempt is made to do a multiple regression using the feartures with the strongest correlation, namely, smoker, age and bmi. The R-squared value is not impressive in this approach.

The predicted error for most points is under 50% for most of the cases and is better for smokers. Some insights after the initial try regarding regression are:

  1. Perhaps it is better to create seperate models for smokers and non smokers
  2. The outliers should have been removed, if they exceed a specific IQR value
  3. The data should have been divided into train and test sets. Using all data might result in over fitting.
model=lm(charges~smoker+age+bmi,df2)
summary(model)

predicted = predict(model,df2)
df3 <- cbind(df,predicted) %>% mutate(error=abs(charges-predicted)/charges*100)
ggplot(df3,aes(x=error, fill=sex)) + 
  geom_histogram(bins = 20) +
  labs(x="Preidction error (%)", y="", title = "Distributiion of predicted errors grouped by smoker") +
  facet_wrap(~ smoker)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
